message:
Could you give an example of why anyone would ever use the "async-aware" signatures of Task.Run? It seems like I could do this:

async Task DoStuff() {  
 ...  
}

async Task Main() {  
 await Task.Run(DoStuff);  
}

...but why wouldn't I just do this?

async Task Main() {  
 await DoStuff();  
}

The latter option seems both more clear and more succinct.

Basically, if one already has a function that returns a Task, why not simply invoke that function to get the Task instead of passing its delegate to Task.Run?
